---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import "../components/styles.css";
---
<Layout>

  <section class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 p-6 bg-black text-white">
    <!-- Motivation -->
    <div class="bg-gray-800 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-6" id="motivation">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-blue-400">Motivation</h2>
        <div class="bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 m-2 flex-1">
          <p>
            Machine learning models are often deployed in <strong class="text-blue-400">dynamic environments</strong> where the data distribution shifts over time.
            Traditional models assume that the test data follows the same distribution as the training data, but in reality, this assumption rarely holds.
            Changes in lighting conditions, sensor noise, environmental factors, or even adversarial perturbations can significantly degrade model performance.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 m-2 flex-1">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-blue-400">Test-time adaptation (TTA)</strong> allows models to adapt to new data distributions without requiring retraining on labeled examples.
            A key approach is <strong class="text-blue-400">Test-Time Adaptation with Pseudo-Labeling (TTAPL)</strong>, which refines predictions using <strong class="text-blue-400">self-generated labels</strong>.
            However, standard TTAPL methods suffer from instability, error accumulation, and overfitting to noisy pseudo-labels.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 m-2 flex-1">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-blue-400">Continual Test-Time Adaptation (CoTTA)</strong> extends TTAPL by incorporating <strong class="text-blue-400">consistency loss and model ensembling techniques</strong>.
            CoTTA applies a blend of <strong class="text-blue-400">self-training and weight perturbations</strong> to prevent catastrophic forgetting and overfitting.
            Our goal is to evaluate <strong class="text-blue-400">how well CoTTA generalizes across different architectures and loss functions</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
    </div>
  
    <!-- Background -->
    <div class="bg-gray-800 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-6 col-span-2" id="background">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-blue-400">Background</h2>
      <div class="bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 m-2">
        <p>
          <strong class="text-blue-400">Test-time adaptation (TTA)</strong> addresses the challenge of <strong class="text-blue-400">distribution shift</strong>—a fundamental problem in machine learning where
          the statistical properties of test data deviate from those observed during training. These shifts occur in various forms, including:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4">
          <li><strong class="text-blue-400">Covariate shift:</strong> Changes in input features, such as variations in image quality or background noise in speech recognition.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-blue-400">Label shift:</strong> Differences in class distributions, where certain categories appear more frequently in deployment than in training.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-blue-400">Concept shift:</strong> Changes in the relationship between input features and labels, such as evolving language patterns in text classification.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 m-2">
        <div class="w-full h-80 flex items-center justify-center rounded-lg">
            <img src="src/images/ttapl.png" alt="TTAPL Flowchart" class="w-full h-full object-contain rounded-lg" />
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 m-2">
        <p class="mt-4">
          To handle these shifts, <strong class="text-blue-400">TTAPL</strong> enables models to adapt at inference time by generating <strong class="text-blue-400">pseudo-labels</strong>.
          However, standard TTAPL methods often face <strong class="text-blue-400">two major challenges</strong>:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4">
          <li><strong class="text-blue-400">Pseudo-label drift:</strong> Incorrect pseudo-labels reinforce model biases, leading to cascading errors.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-blue-400">Overfitting to test samples:</strong> Excessive adaptation to a small set of test data can degrade model generalization.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  
    <!-- Methods -->
    <div class="bg-gray-800 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-6 col-span-2" id="methods">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-blue-400">Methods</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        We evaluated <strong class="text-blue-400">Continual Test-Time Adaptation (CoTTA)</strong>, a method for improving model adaptation to
        distribution shifts without labeled test data. CoTTA leverages <strong class="text-blue-400">pseudo-labeling</strong> and
        <strong class="text-blue-400">consistency loss</strong> to refine predictions dynamically.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 gap-4">
          <p><strong class="text-blue-400">Model Selection:</strong></p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside">
            <li>ResNet</li>
            <li>WideResNet</li>
            <li>PreActResNet</li>
            <li>RLAT</li>
            <li>AugMix-trained models</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 gap-4">
          <p><strong class="text-blue-400">Loss Functions Tested:</strong></p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside">
            <li>Cross-Entropy</li>
            <li>PolyLoss</li>
            <li>KL Divergence</li>
            <li>Cosine Similarity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex justify-center bg-gray-700 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-4 gap-4 mt-4">
        <div class="w-full flex items-center justify-center">
          <img src="src/images/cotta1.png" alt="CoTTA Image 1" class="w-full h-auto object-contain rounded-lg" />
        </div>
        <div class="w-full flex items-center justify-center">
          <img src="src/images/cotta2.png" alt="CoTTA Image 2" class="w-full h-auto object-contain rounded-lg" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  
    <!-- Results -->
    <div class="bg-gray-800 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-6" id="results">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-blue-400">Results</h2>
      <p>
        When <strong class="text-blue-400">model architecture is held constant</strong>, CoTTA with any form of consistency loss demonstrates
        <strong class="text-blue-400">consistent prediction quality</strong>. Accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score improvements remain
        <strong class="text-blue-400">within ±0.01%</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, <strong class="text-blue-400">larger architectures do not necessarily benefit more from CoTTA</strong>, and their complexity may introduce instability in adaptation.
      </p>
      <div class="p-4 bg-gray-700 rounded-lg italic text-center">[Results Table Placeholder]</div>
    </div>
  
    <!-- Contributions -->
    <div class="bg-gray-800 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-6 col-span-2" id="contributions">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-blue-400">Team Contributions</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
        <div class="text-center p-4 border border-gray-600 rounded-lg">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-400">Member 1</h3>
          <p>Developed the adaptive loss function for CoTTA.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center p-4 border border-gray-600 rounded-lg">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-400">Member 2</h3>
          <p>Implemented the evaluation framework and benchmarking.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center p-4 border border-gray-600 rounded-lg">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-400">Member 3</h3>
          <p>Designed and refined the visualization and UI components.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center p-4 border border-gray-600 rounded-lg">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-400">Member 4</h3>
          <p>Handled dataset processing and experimental setup.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  
    <!-- References -->
    <div class="bg-gray-800 shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-6" id="references">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-blue-400">References</h2>
      <p>blahblah</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>